  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency Nutrition and Health Response in Ten Drought-affected Hotspot Priority Woredas (Hadero-Tunto Woreda of Kembata Tenbaro Zone, Soro Woreda of Hadiya Zone, and Humbo Woreda of Wolayita Zone in Southern Nations, Nationalities and Peoples&apos; Region; Ankober, Menz Mama Midir, Minjar Shenkora, and Tarma Ber Woredas of North Shoa Zone in Amhara Region; and Alaltu, Debrelibanos, and Girar Jarso Woredas of North Shoa Zone in Oromia Region) in Ethiopia.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In Ethiopia, 2015 failed rains (Belg and Meher) in main crop-growing regions of the country have led to urgent emergency humanitarian needs. Drought linked to the El Ni&#xF1;o global climatic phenomenon resulted livestock deaths, food insecurity contributing to high rates of malnutrition, and water shortages in affected parts of the country. The number of people requiring assistance in Ethiopia shifted from 4.5 million (in August 2015) up to over 10.2 million individuals as of December 2015. The 2016 Humanitarian Requirements Document estimated 0.4 million SAM cases, 1.7 million MAM cases, and two million people who will encounter lack of safe drinking water in 2016. The most affected parts of the country extend from Tigray in the north down to Southern Nations, Nationalities and Peoples&apos; Region (SNNPR) in the south, to Amhara located more centrally, and to eastern and central Oromia Region.  Hotspot prioritization conducted by the Government of Ethiopia in December 2015 identified that household food security and maternal and child malnutrition situations have deteriorated in the identified 186 hotspot Woredas. Recent assessments conducted in these target Woredas observed that there is an increase in the number of malnutrition cases, deteriorating health conditions at the community level, and decreased crop production. Water shortages are also affecting the health and nutritional status of children, women, and the general population in target Woredas. 
	
Based on the identified gaps, International Medical Corps will provide community- and facility-based support to the target Woredas for the management of acute malnutrition and related health problems. International Medical Corps will strengthen community-based management of acute malnutrition (CMAM) services (stabilization centers (SCs), outpatient therapeutic programme (OTP), targeted supplementary feeding programme (TSFP), and CMAM outreach activities), along with the public health emergency management (PHEM) system.</narrative>
  </description>
